    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>re/those house guests: We live in LA, almost 2,000 miles from family and close friends back in Memphis. We‚Äôre so grateful for them to come that distance to see us that we‚Äôre glad for them stay in our home, as long as they don‚Äôt mind sleeping on the futon in the living room. So when we have house guests, we really HAVE them. We rely on food and cooking to help us get through the strain of total togetherness. Swapping recipes and techniques and sharing the kitchen chores‚Äîand sometimes leaving someone in the kitchen to work the magic all alone‚Äîall help build goodwill when everyone is feeling cranky from too much quality time. And sending them home with a bag of freshly made peanut brittle&#8211;and teaching them how to make it&#8211;helps assuage bad feelings if one of the cats announces, ‚ÄúI‚Äôve had enough company!‚Äù and takes a whiz in a suitcase.</></>Of course, if your guests are people you trust with your jewelry box and your CD collection but not in your kitchen, maybe they SHOULD stay in a hotel!</></>p.s. We‚Äôre having Hasselbacks for din din tonight. Thanks!</p>
    </div>

